======================================================================
SECTION 4: THE JACOBSTHAL CONNECTION
======================================================================

Jacobsthal numbers J(n): recurrence J(n) = J(n-1) + 2*J(n-2)
This is EXACTLY the weighted 2-nacci with weights [1, 2]!
Dominant root = 2 (exact!)

Jacobsthal: [0, 1, 1, 3, 5, 11, 21, 43, 85, 171, 341, 683, 1365, 2731, 5461]
J(n) = (2^n - (-1)^n)/3
  J(0) = 0, formula = 0, match = True
  J(1) = 1, formula = 1, match = True
  J(2) = 1, formula = 1, match = True
  J(3) = 3, formula = 3, match = True
  J(4) = 5, formula = 5, match = True
  J(5) = 11, formula = 11, match = True
  J(6) = 21, formula = 21, match = True
  J(7) = 43, formula = 43, match = True
  J(8) = 85, formula = 85, match = True
  J(9) = 171, formula = 171, match = True
  J(10) = 341, formula = 341, match = True
  J(11) = 683, formula = 683, match = True
  J(12) = 1365, formula = 1365, match = True
  J(13) = 2731, formula = 2731, match = True
  J(14) = 5461, formula = 5461, match = True

Note: J(n) = (2^n - (-1)^n)/3
  At x=2 (OCF point): 2^n is the DOMINANT term
  At x=(-1): (-1)^n is the ALTERNATING correction
  The RATIO is 1/3 — there's the 3!
  J(n) = 2^n/3 - (-1)^n/3
  The 3 in the Jacobsthal formula IS the weighted k-nacci limit!

